Then `output` has ownership of the data, so it won't be affected by lifetime issues. This is safer and idiomatic in Rust.

If your data isn’t copyable or you want to avoid cloning large amounts of data, then explicit lifetimes become even more important.

Yes! That's a very good practice. If you can avoid borrowing across function boundaries by instead transferring ownership or cloning data when needed, you sidestep lifetime problems entirely and make your code safer and easier to reason about.

